The children are allowed to live with the father for a three-year trial period, after which the child will be returned to the mother. During that time, if the mother can prove that the husband is not fit to care for the child, he may lose legal custody; however, this is extremely difficult to prove. Only one of 2,629 divorce petitions resulted in fathers keeping custody. In 1994, Kim Il-sung allowed mothers of children under 16 years old and who were not economic burdens on the state to request permission to be re­employed in leading gender-segregated jobs.

On May 14, the eve of Mother's Day, Workers' Party vice president Mal Yong Tae stated that the party had reviewed ways to ensure that women have the right to raise their children, reminding members of the acceptable age at which newborns should be separated from their mother. The existing law stipulates that nursing mothers may be separated from their children within three years of birth and that divorce cannot take place until after eight months of trial separation. In 1997, because of the shortage of medical supplies for babies under 6 months old and below, 90 percent of mothers were able to see their babies within six weeks of birth. The North Korea - China border is the bustling site of many mothers moving their children and their belongings back and forth illegally.
